  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">PGI - SHO Indonesia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description akvo:type="4" type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Assisting victims of the Central Sulawesi earhquake</narrative>
  </description>
  <description akvo:type="5" type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Member churches of PGI (Communion of Churches in Indonesia)  have been giving assistance to victims of the earthquake in Central Sulawesi since the very first moment. Food, water and clothes are being distributed, trauma healing events are being organized and church -  and community leaders will be trained in disaster management.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description akvo:type="6" type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">On September 28, 2018 at around 17.00 local time a 7.4 magnitude earthquake took place, which was followed by a tsunami that hit the cities of Palu, Donggala and Sigi, in Central Sulawesi, Indonesia, resulting in liquefaction and landslides causing the death of 2.105 people. Palu was the worst affected district, with 1.700 people recorded killed in the city. Search and rescue operations were stopped on 12 October. According to Indonesia&#x2019;s national disaster management agency (BNPB) at least 680 people are reported missing. Ongoing assessments indicate that more than 200.000 people may have been displaced, and at least 110.000 people are staying in displacement sites. 68.000 houses have been destroyed or severely damaged.
Two days after the earthquake, representatives of PGI (Communion of Churches in Indonesia) arrived in the area and started coordinating the humanitarian assistance of churches in Palu and Donggola together with the Synod of PGI member churches in Sulawesi. The synods of the churches include the Central Sulawesi Christian Church (GKST). West Sulawesi Christian Church (GKSB), South Sulawesi Christian Church (GKSS), Indonesian Donggala Protestant Church (GPID), Toraja Church (GT), Masehi Injili Church in Minahasa (GMIM) and SAG Sulutteng.
PGI coordinated with BNPB to procure tents and other assistance. GKST, GKSB, GPID and several other churches have opened humanitarian posts to provide assistance to victims and refugees. PGI noted urgent needs such as clean water, food, proper clothing, medicines, sanitary napkins, sarongs and other basic necessities. In addition to offering primary emergency care, PGI and its member churches will be offering trauma healing to men, women and children. Also, PGI will be providing capacity building (trainer of trainers) to member churches concerning disaster management, disaster risk education and community based disaster preparedness.</narrative>
  </description>
